targets.name: Abell84
targets.desc: This is a faint and relatively small  planetary nebula that is in the Cassopeia constallation

targets.name: Barnard168
targets.desc: Barnard 168 is a dark cloud where star formation can take place. The bright nebula is a separate but connected objected called the Cocoon Nebula. It is located in the Swan constellation and is about 500 light years away from the solar system.

targets.name: Berkeley73
targets.desc: Berkeley 73 is about 1.5 billion years old and is a faint open cluster.

targets.name: CassiopeiaA
targets.desc: This is the youngest known supernova remnant in the Milky Way Galaxy. This was a Type II supernova whose light reached Earth in about 1667, but was not widely seen at that time. This supernovae remnant is 10,000 light years away.

targets.name: CRL2688
targets.desc: Like a baby chick pecking its way out of an egg, the star in the center of the Egg Nebula is casting away shells of gas and dust as it slowly transforms itself into a white dwarf star. The star itself is obscured behind the gas and dust of this protoplanetary nebula. This nebula is 3000 light years away.

targets.name: Czernik12
targets.desc: Czernik12 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Perseus.

targets.name: Czernik27
targets.desc: Czernik27 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Monoceros.

targets.name: Czernik44
targets.desc: Czernik44 is an open cluster in Cassiopeia Constellation

targets.name: Czernik6
targets.desc: Czernik6 is an Open Cluster in the Cassiopeia Constellation. This open cluster only has 6 stars.

targets.name: ESO518-03
targets.desc: ESO518-03 is a globular cluster located in the constellation Ophiuchus. It is 30,300 light years away from earth.

targets.name: ESO587-04
targets.desc: ESO518-03 is a is a globular cluster located in the constellation Ophiuchus. It is 30,300 light years away from earth.

targets.name: HCG16
targets.desc: The galaxies in this group shine brightly with their glowing golden centres and wispy tails of gas, set against a background dotted with much more distant galaxies.

targets.name: HCG21
targets.desc: HCG21 is a Galaxy Cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This group is made up of a set of three spread out galaxies and a fainter pair of galaxies. The brightest galaxy has two extending spiral arms.

targets.name: HCG22
targets.desc: HCG22 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This group consists of a set of three galaxies, including a large elliptical galaxy, and two spiral galaxies.

targets.name: HCG23
targets.desc: HCG23 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This group of galaxies contains a set of four small galaxies and a small very fast moving galaxy.

targets.name: HCG30
targets.desc: HCG30 is a Galaxy cluster in the Eridanus Constellation. This is a spread out set of 4 galaxies where most of them are spiral galaxies.

targets.name: HCG37
targets.desc: HCG37 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cancer Constellation. This set of five galaxies all packed together has two dominant galaxies.

targets.name: HCG4
targets.desc: HCG4 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cetus Constellation.

targets.name: HCG88
targets.desc: HCG88 is a Galaxy cluster in the Aquarius Constellation. This is a loose collection of four spiral galaxies.

targets.name: HCG9
targets.desc: HCG9 is a Galaxy cluster in the Cetus Constellation. This group consists of four galaxies.

targets.name: HCG90
targets.desc: HCG90 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pisces Austrinus Constellation. This is a collection of four interacting galaxies.

targets.name: HCG91
targets.desc: HCG91 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pisces Austrinus Constellation. This group is a collection of four galaxies and contains a set of galaxies that are interacting with each other.

targets.name: HCG92
targets.desc: This is a famous group Stephan's Quintet.  It was the first compact group discovered, it is dense set of four galaxies plus a bright low speed spiral galaxy. Stephan's Quintet is a Galaxy cluster in the Pegasus Constellation.

targets.name: HCG93
targets.desc: HCG93 is a galaxy cluster in the Pegasus Constellation. This group consists of a set of four very similar galaxies plus a fainter galaxy that is moving away from us very quickly.

targets.name: HCG97
targets.desc: HCG97 is a Galaxy cluster in the Pisces Constellation. This group is a loose group of five galaxies.

targets.name: IC1287
targets.desc: IC1287 is a Bright nebula in the Scutum Constellation. This nebula appears blue after reflecting light from the nearby star.

targets.name: IC1318
targets.desc: The Sadr region, or IC 1318, is the nebula surrounding the star called Sadr. The nebula itself is more than 3000 light years away from us.

targets.name: IC1396
targets.desc: The Elephant's Trunk nebula is a concentration of space gas and dust within the much larger nebula of IC 1396 which is located in the constellation Cepheus about 2,400 light years away from Earth.

targets.name: IC1459
targets.desc: IC 1459 is an elliptical galaxy that is about 68.8 million light-years from us in the Constellation of the Crane at the border with the Australian Fish and the Sculptor. This Elliptical galaxy has a supermassive black hole at its centre.

targets.name: IC1795
targets.desc: Located just over 6,000 light-years away, IC1795 is a bright nebula that is located close to the Heart Nebula, IC1805.

targets.name: IC2488
targets.desc: The stars in this open cluster are quite spaced out, and are mainly blue, although there are also a few yellow stars. The cluster itself is around 3700 light years away.

targets.name: IC349
targets.desc: IC 349, also known as Barnard's Merope Nebula, is a nebula which lies 0.06 light years from the star Merope in the Pleiades cluster, Taurus Constellation.  As it is so near to the star, it is quite difficult to observe.

targets.name: IC434
targets.desc: IC 434 is a bright emission nebula in the constellation Orion. It was discovered on February 1, 1786 by William Herschel. This nebula is part of the famous `Horsehead Nebula' in Orion.

targets.name: IC443
targets.desc: IC 443 (also known as the Jellyfish Nebula) is a supernova remnant in the constellation Gemini. It is roughly 5,000 light years from Earth. IC 443 may be the remains of a supernova that occurred 3,000 - 30,000 years ago. A neutron star, the remains of the star which exploded, was recently discovered inside this cloud of glowing gas.

targets.name: IC446
targets.desc: IC446 is a Bright nebula in the Monoceros Constellation. It appears to be several thousand light years behind the more famous Cone Nebula.

targets.name: IC4603
targets.desc: IC4603 is a Bright nebula in the Ophiuchus Constellation. This is one of the nearest star forming regions and the intricacies of the dense interstellar dust clouds in the area provide a spectacular display of light and shade; the contrasting hues making this one of the most dramatic and colourful patches of the entire night sky.

targets.name: IC5146
targets.desc: The Cocoon Nebula is a star forming region. The nebula is lit by the bright young star at the centre. It is roughly 4000 light years away. The dark nebula, Barnard 168, is visible as a dark patch on the edge of the nebula.

targets.name: IC5148
targets.desc: This beautiful planetary nebula was discovered by an amateur astronomer in 1894. It has a hole at its centre surrounding it's central star, enveloped by a ring of material. It is roughly 3449 light years away from us.

targets.name: IC59
targets.desc: This is an emission nebula in the constellation of Cassiopeia.

targets.name: M1
targets.desc: The Crab Nebula is a supernova remnant in the constellation of Taurus. The nebula lies in the Perseus Arm of the Milky Way galaxy, at about 6,500 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M10
targets.desc: Messier 10 or M10 is a globular cluster of stars in the constellation of Ophiuchus and is around 14,400 light years away. The object was discovered by the French astronomer Charles Messier on May 29, 1764, who catalogued it as number 10 in his catalogue and described it as a "nebula without stars".  The hot, young blue stars and the older, yellow stars will be clear to see.

targets.name: M101
targets.desc: This spiral galaxy in the constellation of Ursa Major is more commonly known as the 'Pinwheel Galaxy'. It was discovered in 1781, and was one of the last entries in the Messier Catalogue. M101 has been the location of 3 supernovae events - in 1909, 1951 and 1970. It is around 25 million light years away.

targets.name: M103
targets.desc: This open cluster (also known as NGC581) is situated in the constellation of Cassiopeia. There are about 228 stars in the region of this cluster which have been studied by astronomers - only 77 of which have been found to be in the cluster. Of all the stars in the cluster, there is only 1 red giant star. M103 is around 9000 light years away from us.

targets.name: M107
targets.desc: 21,000 light years away, this globular cluster is approaching us at 147 km/s.

targets.name: M110
targets.desc: Messier 110 is a small elliptical galaxy that is a satellite of the Andromeda Galaxy. M110 contains some dust and hints of recent star formation, which is unusual for small elliptical galaxies.

targets.name: M13
targets.desc: Discovered by Edmond Halley in 1714, this cluster, nicknamed the `Hercules Cluster'  may contain more than a million stars!

targets.name: M15
targets.desc: This is a very dense globular cluster with a concentrated centre which may contain a black hole. At an estimated 12.0 billion years old, it is one of the oldest known globular cluster.

targets.name: M16
targets.desc: Located in Serpens Cauda, this nebula, also known as the 'Eagle nebula', has an open cluster embedded in it, formed from this massive gaseous dusty cloud. This nebula is around 6000 light years away.

targets.name: M18
targets.desc: Messier 18 or M18 is an open cluster of stars in the constellation Sagittarius. This open cluster only has about 20 members. Its age is estimated at 32 million years and it is 4,900 light-years away.

targets.name: M19
targets.desc: Messier 19 is a globular cluster in the constellation Ophiuchus. It was discovered by Charles Messier on June 5, 1764.

targets.name: M2
targets.desc: This globular cluster contains approximately 150,000 stars. It lies around 40,000 light years away.

targets.name: M20
targets.desc: The Trifid Nebula, also known as Messier 20 is in the Sagittarius Constellation. The Trifid Nebula is a star-forming region in the Scutum spiral arm of the Milky Way. The most massive star that has formed in this region has a mass more than 20 times the mass of the Sun. This star is surrounded by a cluster of approximately 3100 young stars.

targets.name: M21
targets.desc: Messier 21 (M21) is an open cluster located in the southern constellation Sagittarius. The cluster lies at about 4,250 light years from Earth. M21 consists mainly of small, faint stars, but is also home to a few blue giants.

targets.name: M22
targets.desc: This globular cluster, discovered in 1665 is one of the nearest globular clusters to us and has a mass of about 1 million Suns. It is roughly 10,400 light years away from us.

targets.name: M26
targets.desc: Open Cluster M26 is an open cluster in the constellation of Scutum. M26 is at a distance of 5,000 light years from the Earth. This cluster is estimated to be 89 million years old.

targets.name: M27
targets.desc: Nicknamed `The Dumbell Nebula', this planetary nebula is an excellent example of a bipolar nebula, whose shape is caused by a hot wind slamming into gas released from the centre of a dying star.

targets.name: M29
targets.desc: Messier 29 is an open cluster located in the constellation Cygnus, the Swan. Messier 29 is too faint to be spotted by the naked eye, but can be seen in binoculars. The cluster lies at an approximate distance of 4,000 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M30
targets.desc: Messier 30 is a globular cluster located in the southern constellation Capricornus. The cluster lies at around 27,140 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M32
targets.desc: Messier 32, also known as Le Gentil, is a dwarf elliptical galaxy located in Andromeda constellation. The galaxy lies at a distance of 2.49 million light years from Earth. M32 is a satellite galaxy of M31, the famous Andromeda Galaxy.

targets.name: M36
targets.desc: Messier 36, also known as the Pinwheel Cluster, is an open cluster located in the northern constellation Auriga, the Charioteer.

targets.name: M37
targets.desc: Messier 37 is the richest open cluster in the constellation Auriga. Messier 37 is the brightest, richest and largest of the three open clusters in this constellation that were catalogued by Messier. The cluster has a distance of 4,511 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M38
targets.desc: Messier 38, also known as the Starfish Cluster, is an open star cluster located in the northern constellation Auriga. The cluster lies at a distance of 4,200 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M42
targets.desc: The Orion Nebula, also known as Messier 42, is a nebula situated in the Milky Way, being south of Orion's Belt in the constellation of Orion. It is one of the brightest nebulae, and is visible to the naked eye in the night sky.

targets.name: M43
targets.desc: Messier 43, also known as De Mairan’s Nebula, is a star-forming nebula located in the constellation Orion. M43 is around 1,600 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M47
targets.desc: Messier 47 is a bright open star cluster located in the southern constellation Puppis. The cluster lies at a distance of 1,600 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M48
targets.desc: Messier 48 is an open star cluster located in Hydra, the largest constellation in the sky. The cluster lies at a distance of 1,500 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M5
targets.desc: Messier 5 is a bright globular cluster located in the northern constellation Serpens. The cluster lies at a distance of 24,500 light years from Earth, in the galactic halo of the Milky Way.

targets.name: M50
targets.desc: Messier 50, nicknamed the Heart-Shaped Cluster, is a large, bright open cluster located in the constellation Monoceros. The cluster is around 3,200 light years away from Earth.

targets.name: M52
targets.desc: Messier 52 is a bright open cluster located in the northern constellation Cassiopeia. The cluster lies at an approximate distance of 5,000 light years from Earth.

targets.name: M57
targets.desc: This Planetary Nebula, also known as the 'Ring Nebula', was thought to have formed 1000 years ago when an old star blew off its surrounding material. The inner part of the nebula which appears dark is actually emitting hot, UV radiation which is invisible to our eyes. The central white dwarf star is planet sized, and was probably once a Sun-like star which blew away its outer layers. At a current tempertaure of 100,000K, the white dwarf will eventually cool down, and after a few billion years, end up as a cold Black Dwarf.

targets.name: M72
targets.desc: Messier 72 is a globular cluster in the Aquarius constellation discovered by French astronomer Pierre Méchain on August 29, 1780. This GC is at a distance of about 53,000 light years. The older, yellow stars and the younger blue stars are clear to see.

targets.name: M74
targets.desc: Messier 74, nicknamed the Phantom Galaxy, is a grand design spiral galaxy located in the constellation Pisces. The galaxy looks like its facing the Earth face-on. It lies at an approximate distance of 30 million light years from Earth.

targets.name: M78
targets.desc: This nebula in Orion is an active star forming region, illuminated by the bright stars inside the nebula. This nebula is part of a larger molecular cloud and is around 1500 light years from us.

targets.name: M8
targets.desc: The Lagoon Nebula, M8, is a giant interstellar cloud in the constellation Sagittarius. The Lagoon Nebula is estimated to be between 4,000-6,000 light-years from the Earth.

targets.name: M81
targets.desc: Messier 81 (also known as Bode's Galaxy) is a spiral galaxy about 12 million light-years away in the constellation Ursa Major.

targets.name: M82
targets.desc: This is an irregular galaxy in the constellation of Ursa Major, 13 million light years away. It is one of a group of galaxies, and is thought to have recently been involved in an interaction with its close neighbour, the spiral galaxy, M81. It is this interaction which is thought to have caused the dust lanes which are prominent in this galaxy, and visible as the dark patches throughout the galaxy.

targets.name: M9
targets.desc: M9 is a globular cluster located 25,800 light years away in the constellation Ophiuchus. It is one of the closest clusters to the centre of our galaxy.

targets.name: M93
targets.desc: M93 (also known as NGC 2447) is an open cluster located 3,600 light years away in the constellation Puppis. The cluster is about 100 million years old.

targets.name: Mayer2
targets.desc: The Mayer2 is an open galactic cluster.

targets.name: NGC0371
targets.desc: NGC0371 is a bright open cluster situated 210,000 light years away in the Small Magellanic cloud, a small irregular galaxy orbiting our Milky Way galaxy.

targets.name: NGC1003
targets.desc: NGC1003 is a spiral galaxy located in the Perseus constellation about 28 million light years from the Milky Way. It was discovered by the German-British astronomer William Herschel in 1784.

targets.name: NGC1023
targets.desc: NGC1023 is a barred lenticular galaxy - it has a disk and central bulge like our Galaxy, but no spiral arms. The galaxies lies between between 30 and 64 million light years away. By studying the velocities of the stars at its centre, astronomers have deduced that there must be a supermassive black hole the centre of this galaxy.

targets.name: NGC1049
targets.desc: NGC 1049 is a globular cluster located in the Fornax Dwarf galaxy. At a distance of 630,000 light years, it is visible in moderate sized telescopes, while the parent galaxy is nearly invisible.

targets.name: NGC1140
targets.desc: NGC 1140 is an irregular galaxy in the southern constellation of Eridanus. It is 59 million light years away and is forming stars very rapidly.

targets.name: NGC1179
targets.desc: NGC1179 is a faint face-on spiral galaxy in the constellation of Eridanus.

targets.name: NGC1193
targets.desc: NGC1193 is an old open cluster is located in the constellation Perseus.

targets.name: NGC121
targets.desc: NGC 121 is a globular cluster located 210, 000 light years away in the Small Magellanic Cloud a nearby dwarf galaxy. It was first discovered by John Herschel on September 20, 1835.

targets.name: NGC1232
targets.desc: This is a beautiful face-on spiral in the Eridanus cluster, located about 70 million light years away. Regions where stars are forming in the spiral arms can clearly be seen as blue `knots' along the arms.

targets.name: NGC1300
targets.desc: This is an excellent example of a barred spiral galaxy. The central bar is clear to see coming out from the central bulge, with the spiral arms located at the end of the bar.

targets.name: NGC1325
targets.desc: NGC 1325 is a barred spiral galaxy of Hubble type SA (s) bc in the constellation Eridanus at the southern sky. The galaxy was discovered by the astronomer William Herschel on 19 December 1798.

targets.name: NGC1332
targets.desc: NGC1332 is a lenticular galaxy in the Eridanus galaxy cluster around 75 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC1348
targets.desc: NGC1348 is an open cluster located around 6,194 light years in the Perseus Constellation. The cluster only contains about 20 stars.

targets.name: NGC1385
targets.desc: NGC1385 is a spiral galaxy with an irregular appearance located in the Eridanus galaxy cluster.

targets.name: NGC1395
targets.desc: NGC1395 is a seyfert galaxy meaning the centre of the galaxy (called the nucleus) is small and intensely bright.

targets.name: NGC1407
targets.desc: NGC1407 is an elliptical galaxy lying about 70 million light years away in the Eridanus galaxy cluster.

targets.name: NGC1426
targets.desc: NGC1426 is a rather small elliptical galaxy in the Eridanus galaxy cluster.

targets.name: NGC1491
targets.desc: NGC1491 is an emission nebula located 12,000 light years away in the constellation of Perseus. The nebula can be seeing glows red. Strong, energetic winds from this star are blowing the surrounding gas away from the star, giving it a bubble like appearance.

targets.name: NGC1501
targets.desc: NGC1501 is an elliptical-shaped planetary nebula located 5,000 light years away in the constellation of Camelopardalis. The nebula has a very hot (100,000K) so-called Wolf-Rayet star at its centre ejecting its mass at very high speeds as it approaches the end of its life.

targets.name: NGC1514
targets.desc: NGC1535 is a spherical-looking planetary nebula located around 4,000 light years away. It was discovered in 1790 by William Herschel.

targets.name: NGC1532
targets.desc: Also known as Haley's Coronet, NGC 1532 is an edge-on spiral galaxy discovered by James Dunlop in 1826. It has a dwarf galaxy in the process of merging with it.

targets.name: NGC1532
targets.desc: Also known as Haley's Coronet, NGC 1532 is an edge-on spiral galaxy discovered by James Dunlop in 1826. It has a dwarf galaxy in the process of merging with it.

targets.name: NGC1555
targets.desc: NGC1555 is a diffuse nebula lit up by a star within the Taurus constellation.

targets.name: NGC1605
targets.desc: NGC1605 is an open cluster located 8,342 light years away in the Perseus constellation.

targets.name: NGC1624
targets.desc: NGC1624 is an open star cluster made up of just a few stars embedded within a diffuse reddish nebula.

targets.name: NGC1788
targets.desc: NGC1788 is a reflection nebula located 2000 light years away in the constellation of Orion. The nebula appears blue in colour due to blue light scattering off gas and dust in the nebula.

targets.name: NGC1798
targets.desc: NGC1798 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Auriga. It has about 50 member stars and a number of faint background stars can be seen.

targets.name: NGC185
targets.desc: NGC 185 (also known as Caldwell 18) is a dwarf spheroidal galaxy located 2 million light-years in the constellation Cassiopeia. It is a satellite of the Andromeda Galaxy.

targets.name: NGC1883
targets.desc: NGC1883 is an open cluster located 15,648 light years away in the constellation Auriga and is about a billion years old.

targets.name: NGC1931
targets.desc: NGC1931 is an open cluster and emission nebula approximately 7000 light years away. At 10 million years old, this is fairly young, hence why the emission nebula from which the stars formed, is still visible.

targets.name: NGC1999
targets.desc: NGC1999 is a emission and reflection nebula located 1,000 light years away in the constellation of Orion. This nebula is lit up by its central star, V380.

targets.name: NGC2024
targets.desc: NGC 2024, sometimes known as the "Flame Nebula", is a star-forming region located near the star Zeta Orionis in Orion's Belt.

targets.name: NGC2129
targets.desc: NGC2129 has been classified as a young open cluster located 5,000 light years away, however recent studies have found that a number of stars in this cluster are actually at a variety of distances.

targets.name: NGC2146
targets.desc: NGC2146 is a barred spiral galaxy that has been part of an interaction with another galaxy, resulting in its peculiar shape.

targets.name: NGC2158
targets.desc: NGC2158 is a well-populated open cluster with about 1000 star members, making it look similar to a globular cluster. The cluster is located 16,000 light years.

targets.name: NGC2169
targets.desc: NGC2169 is an open cluster located 3,000 light years away. It was discovered in 1784 by William Herschel.

targets.name: NGC2186
targets.desc: NGC2186 is an open cluster located 5,000 light years away. It was discovered in 1786 by William Herschel.

targets.name: NGC2207
targets.desc: NGC2207 and IC2163 are a pair of colliding spiral galaxies in the constellation Canis Major. They were both discovered by John Herschel in 1835, and are located about 80 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC2225
targets.desc: NGC2225 is a small open cluster with about 40 member stars, located in the constellation of Monoceros.

targets.name: NGC2245
targets.desc: NGC2245 is a nebula made up of gas and dust reflecting light from a nearby star.

targets.name: NGC2247
targets.desc: NGC2247 is a reflection nebula located in the constellation of Monoceros. It appears as a faint, hazy circular glow surrounding a brighter star.

targets.name: NGC2261
targets.desc: NGC2261 is a reflection nebula lit up by a variable star at the lower part of the nebula. It's located about 2,500 light years away.

targets.name: NGC2266
targets.desc: NGC2266 is an open cluster containing about 190 stars, many of which are red giants who are in the phase of their evolution where they are burning a shell of Hydrogen around their core. The blue stars in the cluster are still burning the Hydrogen in their core. The galaxy is located about 11,000 light years away.

targets.name: NGC2298
targets.desc: NGC2298 is a small globular cluster located 34,900 light years away. It was discovered in 1826 by James Dunlop.

targets.name: NGC2359
targets.desc: NGC2359 is an emission nebula nicknamed 'Thor's Helmet' or the 'Duck Nebula'. It is located 16,000 light years away and lit up by a bright so-called Woif-Rayet star.

targets.name: NGC2392
targets.desc: NGC2392 is a stunning planetary nebula located 5,000 light years away. Due to its shape, it has been nicknamed 'The Clown Face Nebula' or 'The Eskimo Nebula'.

targets.name: NGC2403
targets.desc: NGC2403 is a spiral galaxy located 11.5 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC2419
targets.desc: NGC2419 is a globular cluster nicknamed 'The Intergalactic Wanderer', as it was originally thought to be an intergalactic cluster.  We now know that it is gravitationally bound to our Galaxy and is one of the most luminous GCs in our Galaxy.

targets.name: NGC2438
targets.desc: NGC2438 is a ring-shaped planetary nebula located 2,900 light years away. It was discovered by William Herschel in 1786.

targets.name: NGC2440
targets.desc: NGC2440 is a planetary nebula located 3,600 light years away. It is an interesting nebula with a lot of structure on its outskirts.

targets.name: NGC246
targets.desc: NGC246 is a planetary nebula. The central star has a temperature of over 130,000 K, compared to our Sun, which shines at just 6000 K.

targets.name: NGC2467
targets.desc: NGC2467 is an open cluster s surround by a diffuse nebulosity. It is located 17,000 light years away in the constellation of Puppis.

targets.name: NGC2525
targets.desc: NGC2525 is an impressive face-on barred spiral galaxy located 68 million light years away in the Puppis constellation.

targets.name: NGC2613
targets.desc: NGC2613 is a fine example of a spiral galaxy inclined from our line of sight so that we see it nearly edge-on. It's located 65 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC2626
targets.desc: NGC2626 is a reflection nebula located 3,300 light years lit up largely by a central, blue star.

targets.name: NGC2627
targets.desc: NGC 2627 is an open cluster located 6,500 light years away, containing about 60 faint stars.

targets.name: NGC2655
targets.desc: NGC2655 is a lenticular galaxy (a disk galaxy, similar to the Milky Way, but with no spiral arm structure) about 80 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC2658
targets.desc: NGC2658 is an open cluster contains about 80 stars. It lies about 1,532 light years away.

targets.name: NGC2660
targets.desc: NGC2660 is an open cluster that looks very similar to a globular cluster. It lies 9,212 light years.

targets.name: NGC2681
targets.desc: NGC2681 is a lenticular galaxy (a disk galaxy, similar to the Milky Way, but with no spiral arm structure) about 45 million light years away in the constellation of Ursa Major. Its centre is thought to contain a black-hole with a mass of about 8 million suns.

targets.name: NGC2683
targets.desc: NGC2683 is a nearly edge-on spiral galaxy at a distance of about 30 million light years.

targets.name: NGC2693
targets.desc: NGC2693 is an 'elliptical' galaxy, a type without spiral arms, lying 186 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC281
targets.desc: NGC281 is also known as the 'Pac-man' nebula due to its shape. Lying 10,000 light years away, it is a busy workshop of star formation. Prominent features include a small open cluster of stars, a diffuse red-glowing emission nebula, large lanes of obscuring gas and dust, and dense knots of dust and gas in which stars may still be forming.

targets.name: NGC2818A
targets.desc: NGC2818A is a planetary nebula situated in an open cluster consisting of massive stars, most of which have ended their lives as supernovae and disappeared. In this cluster, one of the stars has shed its material resulting in the planetary nebula.

targets.name: NGC288
targets.desc: NGC288 is a globular cluster located 30,000 light years away in the constellation of Sculptor. It was discovered in 1785 by William Herschel. It contains over 100,000 as much material as the Sun.

targets.name: NGC2903
targets.desc: NGC2903 is a barred spiral galaxy approximately 30 million light years away. It has a rather mottled appearance due to the many star-forming regions in its spiral arms which show up as bright spots along the arms.

targets.name: NGC3184
targets.desc: NGC3184 is a nearly face-on spiral galaxy, about 30 million light years away. It has several bright regions visible in its spiral arms, which are the sites of star formation.

targets.name: NGC3231
targets.desc: NGC3231 is an open cluster in the constellation of Ursa Major.

targets.name: NGC346
targets.desc: NGC346 is an open cluster found in the Small Magellanic Cloud, a small irregular galaxy orbiting our Milky Way Galaxy 210,000 light years away.

targets.name: NGC40
targets.desc: NGC40 is a planetary nebula located 3,000 light years away in the constellation Cepheus. The central star of this planetary nebula is a 'Wolf-Rayet' star. This type of star is very hot (100,000K) and blowing off it's mass at very high speeds as it nears the end of its life.

targets.name: NGC457
targets.desc: NGC457 is the brightest star cluster in the Cassiopeia constellation, 2,145 light years away. It is composed of around 80 stars, and is often called the 'Owl' or 'ET' cluster owing to its shape.

targets.name: NGC5204
targets.desc: NGC5204 has been classified by astronomers as a spiral and irregular galaxy, due to the appearance of its spiral arms, which are not very well defined. It has quite a bright centre.

targets.name: NGC5466
targets.desc: NGC5466 is a globular cluster 55,000 light years away in the constellation of Bootes. It contains 3 binary star systems, an extremely rare occurrence in globular clusters where 2 stars orbit around each other.

targets.name: NGC5474
targets.desc: NGC5474 is a nearly face-on spiral galaxy 20 million light years away. It is very interesting to observe as, ulike most galaxy cores, this one appears somewhat offset from the centre of the galaxy, due to the gravitational interaction that this galaxy is undergoing with its large neighbour, M101.

targets.name: NGC 55
targets.desc: NGC 55 is mostly likely a spiral galaxy with a bar through its centre. Its irregular shape comes from it being viewed almost edge-on, from Earth.

targets.name: NGC5617
targets.desc: NGC5617 is an open cluster 2,600 light years away.

targets.name: NGC5694
targets.desc: NGC5694 is a small, densely packed globular cluster in the constellation of Hydra, 113,000 light years away.

targets.name: NGC5806
targets.desc: NGC5806 is a faint, barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Virgo.

targets.name: NGC5812
targets.desc: NGC5812 is an elliptical galaxy in the constellation of Libra.

targets.name: NGC5897
targets.desc: NGC5897 is a globular cluster with a mass of 200,000 suns. It contains about 40 so-called 'blue stragglers' - these are stars which are bright and blue, and therefore appear younger than the globular cluster's age. A possible reason for this is that they may have lost their outer layers during collisions with other stars.

targets.name: NGC5921
targets.desc: NGC5921 is a small barred spiral galaxy is at the centre of Serpens Caput (the head of the snake depicting the constellation Serpens).

targets.name: NGC5964
targets.desc: NGC5964 is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Serpens.

targets.name: NGC5998
targets.desc: NGC5998 open cluster is located in the constellation of Scorpius.

targets.name: NGC6015
targets.desc: NGC6015 is a spiral galaxy in the constellation of Draco about 50 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC6025
targets.desc: NGC6025 open cluster that was discovered in 1751. The presence of very faint unresolved stars in this cluster gives the appearance of a faint nebula throughout the area.

targets.name: NGC6027
targets.desc: NGC 6027 can be seen with other galaxies, all of which are part of a group of galaxies, known as Seyfert's Sextet. The group is interesting to astronomers since five of the galaxies have very similar velocities, implying they are all at around the same distance from Earth, except the small spiral galaxy which a velocity nearly four times larger than the others!

targets.name: NGC6041
targets.desc: NGC 6041 is a bright lenticular galaxy, meaning it is between an elliptical and a spiral. It is located in the constellation Hercules and about 400,000 light years  from Earth.

targets.name: NGC6093
targets.desc: NGC6093 is a globular cluster 30,000 light years away, also known as M80 contains a large number of 'blue stragglers' - stars which are bright and blue, and therefore appear younger than the globular cluster's age. A possible reason for this is that they may have lost their outer layers during collisions with other stars.

targets.name: NGC6118
targets.desc: NGC6118 is a faint spiral galaxy in the constellation of Serpens.

targets.name: NGC6144
targets.desc: NGC 6144 is a globular cluster in the constellation Scorpius 33,500 light years away. This globular cluster is moving away from us at about 102 km per second.

targets.name: NGC6181
targets.desc: NGC 6181 is a barred spiral galaxy located in the constellation Hercules, 107 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC6207
targets.desc: NGC 6207 is a spiral galaxy located in the constellation Hercules. NGC 6207 is located at about 30 million light years from earth near the globular cluster Messier 13.

targets.name: NGC6229
targets.desc: NGC6229 is a globular cluster located 99,000 light years away. It was discovered by William Herschel in 1787 and wrongly classified as planetary nebula. Its correct identification was made in the mid 19th century.

targets.name: NGC6340
targets.desc: NGC6340 is a lenticular galaxy - a disk galaxy similar to a spiral, but with no spiral arms.

targets.name: NGC6341
targets.desc: NGC6341 is a globular cluster located 26,700 light years away. This cluster contains a few variable stars, and also an eclipsing binary star system (two stars orbiting each other along our line of sight), which are rare in such objects.

targets.name: NGC6366
targets.desc: NGC6366 is a very diffuse globular cluster, which looks similar to an open cluster. Unlike many other globular clusters, it is rather rich in elements heavier than Helium, thus it is said to be 'metal-rich'.

targets.name: NGC637
targets.desc: NGC637 is an open cluster is located in the constellation of Cassiopeia about 7,000 light years away.

targets.name: NGC6384
targets.desc: NGC6384 is a face-on spiral galaxy about 60 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC6426
targets.desc: NGC 6426 is a globular cluster located in the constellation Ophiuchus, 66,500 light years away.

targets.name: NGC6440
targets.desc: NGC6440 is a centrally concentrated globular cluster was discovered in 1784 by William Herschel.

targets.name: NGC6503
targets.desc: NGC6503 is a nearly edge-on spiral galaxy about 17 million light years away.

targets.name: NGC6517
targets.desc: NGC6517 is a globular cluster about 70,000 light years away, lying on the far side of our Galaxy.

targets.name: NGC6522
targets.desc: NGC6522 is a globular cluster lying at a distance of 25,400 light years, in the direction of our Galaxy's centre.

targets.name: NGC6535
targets.desc: NGC6535 is a globular cluster situated 22,000 light years away in Serpens.

targets.name: NGC6539
targets.desc: NGC6539 is a globular cluster, located 27,000 light years away in the constellation Serpens.

targets.name: NGC6553
targets.desc: NGC6553 is a globular cluster located 18,250 light years away. It is located in the central bulge of our Galaxy, and is therefore obscured slightly by gas and dust.

targets.name: NGC6590
targets.desc: NGC6590 is a small reflection nebula in the constellation of Sagittarius, lit by the stars embedded in it.

targets.name: NGC6611
targets.desc: NGC6611 is an open cluster, also known as M16, located 7,000 light years away. The cluster is embedded in a cloud of gas known as the Eagle nebula, from which it formed. It is in fact the light from the young, hot stars in this cluster which excites the gas cloud and causes it to shine.

targets.name: NGC6643
targets.desc: NGC6643 is a spiral galaxy with a small nucleus (centre) and spiral arms.

targets.name: NGC6654
targets.desc: NGC6654 is a faint galaxy in the constellation of Draco. It is classified as a barred lenticular galaxy, meaning that it has a disk shape (as do spiral galaxies) with a bar running through the centre, but it has no spiral arms.

targets.name: NGC6684
targets.desc: NGC6684 is a barred spiral galaxy 37 million light years away in the constellation Pavo.

targets.name: NGC6703
targets.desc: NGC6703 is a lenticular galaxy in the constellation of Lyra. Lenticular galaxies have a disc-shape, similar to our Galaxy, but no spiral arms.

targets.name: NGC6712
targets.desc: NGC6712 is a globular cluster located 25,000 light years from Earth. The cluster passed through the plane of the Milky Way a few million years ago - the result of such interactions is that many of the lighter stars in this cluster have been stripped away, leaving only about 1% of its original mass. It is one of around 12 globular cluster in the galaxy which is a bright source of X-rays.

targets.name: NGC6720
targets.desc: NGC6720 is a planetary nebula, also known as the 'Ring Nebula', located 2,000 light years from Earth. It is thought to have formed 1,000 years ago when an old star blew off its surrounding material. The inner part of the nebula which appears dark is actually emitting hot, UV radiation which is invisible to our eyes. The central white dwarf star is planet-sized, and was probably once a Sun-like star.

targets.name: NGC6749
targets.desc: NGC6749 is a globular cluster 25,800 light years away in the constellation Aquila. It is is very diffuse and appears similar to an open cluster.

targets.name: NGC6756
targets.desc: NGC6756 is an open cluster 11,000 light years away in the constellation of Aquila. It  contains about 40 member stars.

targets.name: NGC6802
targets.desc: NGC6802 is an open cluster 4,000 light years away in the constellation of Vulpecula is relatively old and small.

targets.name: NGC6804
targets.desc: NGC6804 is a planetary nebula. The central star in this nebula can be seen clearly with its expanding shells of gas.

targets.name: NGC6814
targets.desc: NGC6814 is a face-on spiral galaxy, which can be viewed through the inner arm of our own galaxy, the Milky Way.

targets.name: NGC6819
targets.desc: NGC 6819 is an open cluster located 7,200 light years away in the Cygnus constellation. NGC6819 is a relatively small open cluster containing about 150 stars. It is also known as the 'Foxhead' star cluster.

targets.name: NGC6826
targets.desc: NGC6826 is a planetary nebula lying 3,000 light years away in the constellation of Cygnus. It is nicknamed the 'Blinking Nebula'. The central star is at a temperature of 45,000K and is 0.6 times more massive than our Sun. It is also one of the brightest central stars in all the planetary nebula which are visible.

targets.name: NGC6838
targets.desc: NGC6838 is a loose globular cluster, although for a long period of time many astronomers considered it to be a dense open cluster. It lies 13,000 light years from Earth.

targets.name: NGC6842
targets.desc: NGC6842 is quite a faint planetary nebula in the constellation of Vulpecula. It was first discovered by Albert Marth on June 28, 1863.

targets.name: NGC6866
targets.desc: NGC 6866 is an open cluster 5,000 light years away in the constellation Cygnus. It was discovered by Caroline Herschel on 23 July 1783.

targets.name: NGC6872
targets.desc: NGC6872, known as the Condor galaxy, is a barred spiral galaxy in the constellation Pavo. This galaxy is approximately 5 billion years old, and is interacting with the much smaller lenticular galaxy IC4970.

targets.name: NGC6888
targets.desc: NGC6888, also known as the Crescent Nebula, is an emission nebula in the constellation Cygnus, about 5000 light-years away from Earth. It was discovered by Friedrich Wilhelm Herschel in 1792. It is formed by the fast stellar wind from the Wolf-Rayet star WR 136 (HD 192163) colliding with and energizing the slower moving wind ejected by the star when it became a red giant around 250,000 to 400,000 years ago.

targets.name: NGC6894
targets.desc: NGC6894 is a planetary nebula 4,000 light years away in the Cygnus constellation. The nebula is slightly pink in colour - due most likely to reddening of its light by dust clouds between ourselves and the nebula.

targets.name: NGC6907
targets.desc: NGC6907 is a barred spiral galaxy 137 million light years away with clearly defined, spread out spiral arms and a bar through the central of the galaxy.

targets.name: NGC6910
targets.desc: NGC 6910 is a young open cluster visible in the Swan constellation 4,000 light years away.

targets.name: NGC6913
targets.desc: NGC6913 (also known as M29) is a young open cluster located 3,000 light years away in the constellation Cygnus. It contains about 50  stars. There is a lot of dust between ourselves and this cluster, dimming the light from the stars.

targets.name: NGC6914
targets.desc: NGC 6914 is a reflection nebula located at approximately 6,000 light-years away in the constellation of Cygnus, and was discovered by Édouard Stephan on August 29, 1881.

targets.name: NGC6934
targets.desc: NGC6934 is a globular cluster in the constellation of Delphinus, 50,000 light years away in the halo of our Galaxy. It has a mass of about 200,000 Suns, and is though to be a remnant of a tidally disrupted dwarf galaxy which was orbiting the Milky Way.

targets.name: NGC6946
targets.desc: NGC 6946 (also tentatively known as the Fireworks Galaxy) is a spiral galax,y about 22 million light-years away, in the constellations of Cepheus and Cygnus.

targets.name: NGC6951
targets.desc: NGC6951 is a good example of a barred spiral galaxy, as the bar can be clearly seen stretching out from the centre of this galaxy. Two supernovae have gone off in this galaxy, one in 1999 and one in 2000.

targets.name: NGC6960
targets.desc: NGC6960 is part of the enormous "Veil Nebula" - the gas left behind after the detonation of a supernova. The nebula is around 2,000 light years distant, and has a diameter of around 100 light years.

targets.name: NGC7000
targets.desc: NGC7000, known as the North America nebula, is an emission nebula in the constellation Cygnus, 1,600 light years away, close to Deneb. The remarkable shape of the nebula resembles that of the continent of North America, complete with a prominent Gulf of Mexico.

targets.name: NGC7006
targets.desc: NGC 7006 (also known as Caldwell 42) is a globular cluster in the constellation Delphinus. NGC 7006 resides in the outskirts of the Milky Way. It is about 135,000 light-years away, five times the distance between the Sun and the centre of the galaxy, and it is part of the galactic halo.

targets.name: NGC7008
targets.desc: NGC 7008, also known as the Fetus Nebula, is a planetary nebula with a diameter of approximately 1 light-year located at a distance of 2800 light years in the Cygnus constellation.

targets.name: NGC7023
targets.desc: NGC 7023 is actually the cluster within the nebula known as the Iris Nebula and Caldwell 4 - a bright reflection nebula in the constellation Cepheus 1,300 light years away.

targets.name: NGC7036
targets.desc: NGC7036's nature is unknown. The object was investigated by professional astronomers in 2002, as there was some uncertainty as to whether or not it actually is a star cluster or just a projection of stars at varying distances, on the sky. Its nature is still undetermined.

targets.name: NGC7048
targets.desc: NGC 7048 is a planetary nebula in the constellation of Cygnus. The bright star to the lower left of the nebula is a magnitude 10.5 star, designated TYC 3589-4652-1. The central star of NGC 7048 is though to be a white dwarf.

targets.name: NGC7102
targets.desc: NGC7102 is a distant barred spiral galaxy in the constellation of Pegasus. It has a small bright nucleus with a central bar.

targets.name: NGC7128
targets.desc: NGC7128 is an open cluster 13,000 light years away in the Cygnus Constellation. It was first discovered by William Herschel on October 14, 1787.

targets.name: NGC7129
targets.desc: NGC 7129 is a reflection nebula located 3,300 light years away in the constellation Cepheus. A young open cluster is responsible for illuminating the surrounding nebula. A recent survey indicates the cluster contains more than 130 stars less than 1 million years old.

targets.name: NGC7213
targets.desc: NGC7213 is one of the brightest of the spirals in the constellation of Grus, 70 million light years ago.

targets.name: NGC7293
targets.desc: NGC7293, also known as the Helix Nebula, is a large planetary nebula located in the constellation Aquarius. The Helix Nebula is relatively close, at a distance of around 450 light years.

targets.name: NGC7296
targets.desc: NGC7296 is an open cluster located in the constellation of Lacerta. This object is considered to be the same as NGC 7295.

targets.name: NGC7331
targets.desc: NGC7331 is a spiral galaxy an estimated 50 million light years away. X-ray observations suggest that the centre of this galaxy may contain a massive black hole.

targets.name: NGC7410
targets.desc: NGC7410 is a spiral galaxy seen slightly edge-on, thus appears quite elongated. It lies 76 million light years from Earth.

targets.name: NGC7418
targets.desc: NGC 7418 is a barred spiral galaxy and is located 63 million light years away in the Crane Constellation.

targets.name: NGC7418A
targets.desc: NGC7418A is a spiral galaxy with a brighter central region and fainter, diffuse spiral arms. NGC7418A lies 91 million light years away in the Grus Constellation.

targets.name: NGC7479
targets.desc: NGC 7479 (also known as Caldwell 44) is a barred spiral galaxy about 105 million light-years away in the constellation Pegasus. This is a beautiful barred spiral galaxy, seen almost face on.

targets.name: NGC7492
targets.desc: NGC7492 is a very loosely concentrated globular cluster,  one of the furthest GCs from us at a distance of 84,100 light years. NGC7492 is in the constellation Aquarius.

targets.name: NGC7635
targets.desc: NGC7635, also known as Bubble Nebula, is a nebula that shines because it is heated by energy from a star almost 20 times as massive as our Sun.  The nebula lies 11,300 light years away.

targets.name: NGC7654
targets.desc: NGC7654, also known as M52,  is a fine open cluster with 200 members. It has two yellow giant stars which are brighter than the others and lies 5,000 light years from Earth.

targets.name: NGC772
targets.desc: NGC772 is an unbarred spiral galaxy approximately 130 million light-years away in the constellation Aries.

targets.name: NGC7788
targets.desc: NGC7788 is a scattered cluster of about 25 stars in the constellation of Cassiopeia. NGC 7788 was first identified by John Herschel in 1829.

targets.name: NGC7789
targets.desc: NGC 7789 is an open cluster in the constellation Cassiopeia, that was discovered by Caroline Herschel in 1783. Her brother William Herschel included it in his catalogue as H VI.30. This cluster is also known as "The White Rose" Cluster or "Caroline's Rose" Cluster because when seen visually, the loops of stars and dark lanes look like the swirling pattern of rose petals as seen from above. It lies 7600 light years from Earth.

targets.name: NGC7814
targets.desc: NGC 7814 (also known as UGC 8 or Caldwell 43) is a spiral galaxy about 40 million light-years away in the constellation Pegasus. The galaxy is seen edge-on from Earth. It is sometimes referred to as "the little sombrero", a miniature version of Messier 104.

targets.name: NGC7822
targets.desc: NGC 7822 is a young star-forming complex in the constellation of Cepheus. The complex is believed to be some 2,900 light years distant, with the younger components aged no more than a few million years.

targets.name: NGC7833
targets.desc: NGC7833 is an open cluster consisting of only 4 stars in the constellation of Pegasus.

targets.name: NGC925
targets.desc: NGC 925 is a barred spiral galaxy located about 30 million light-years away in the constellation Triangulum.

targets.name: NGC936
targets.desc: NGC936 is a barred lenticular galaxy - it has a disc shape with a central bar, but no spiral arms.

targets.name: NGC949
targets.desc: NGC949 is a small spiral galaxy in the NGC1023 galaxy group. The galaxy has an unusual shape, made more obscure due to its inclination.

targets.name: PK315-0.1
targets.desc: PK315-0.1 is a fairly bright planetary nebula in the constellation of Centaurus, just 6.7 light years away.

targets.name: PNG144.3-15.5
targets.desc: PNG144.3-15.5 is quite a small Planetary Nebula.

targets.name: Ruprecht135
targets.desc: Ruprecht135 is an open galactic cluster that is moving towards us at 0.71 km per second.

targets.name: Ruprecht26
targets.desc: Ruprecht26 is a open cluster that is located in the constellation of Puppis.

targets.name: Sh2-155
targets.desc: Sh2-155 is a nebula visible due to the energy from young stars, embedded within, which ionises the cloud of cool gas.

targets.name: Tycho's SNR
targets.desc: Tycho'sSNR is a supernova remnant observed by Tycho Brahe on November 11, 1572. Although it lies 10,000 light years away, the object was as bright as Venus for many months, now all that is left is this faint nebulosity.

targets.name: UGCA91
targets.desc: UGCA91 is a globular cluster lying 294,000 light years away, making it one of the most distant globular clusters around the Milky Way.
